deck_excerpt: G Golem Code Talker Tri-Gate Magician Budget
deck_description:
Hey I'm back with another budget deck for starter players. This decks main focus is to bring out powerful link monsters and climb to a end board with some interuption using monsters like Firewall Dragon , Tri-gate Wizard , Decode Talker Heatsoul  (Free Draws) and the G-Golem Boss Monsters to co-colink to other monster and make them immune to opponent monster effects. This deck has the ability to link climb very nicely with the G-Golem Link-2s , Splash Mage  and Transcode Talker . 

Many of the monster in deck as well can be used from hand to link and search and recycle cards on top of that.

The main goal of this deck is to be cheap enough for new players to afford and be competitve enough that they can confidently learn the game and jumo into complicated game play over time. This deck gets better the more you play it so get dueling.

-Copperblade

It might not be the best possible deck, but I like Orcust and I've been getting a 75% winrate with it.

NOTE: Fossil Dig and Scrapyard are completely interchangeable, as both exist to search exactly Scrap Raptor and nothing else. I would run 2 digs if I had them, because it's more generic, but it's also a UR, so...

General gameplan is to use scrap recycler, dark grepher, girsu, or armageddon knight to send a harp horror to GY and do Orcust stuff.

There is an extended scrap combo you can do if you open scrap recycler (or a way to it) and don't draw your garnets (golem, rosenix, world wand... yeah i know). It takes advantage of Golem and Recycler not being once per turn to use them multiple times in a turn. Combo is as follows:

  1. Recycler sends Rosenix to GY
  2. Rosenix effect to summon token (sometimes a Danger! in hand can be used instead if you got ashed or something)
  3. Link Scrap Wyvern
  4. Wyvern effect to summon a scrap from GY and immediately pop it, to trigger 2nd effect:
  5. Use Wyvern's 2nd effect to summon Scrap Golem from deck and then pop the wyvern (or a set spell you don't need, or an opponent's card if you're not on turn 1)
  6. Golem effect to summon Recycler
  7. Recycler sends World Wand to GY
  8. This allows us to link summon Lib with golem and recycler
  9. Lib effect to set World Legacy Succession (if it's not already in hand)
  10. Succession to bring back Golem
  11. Golem to bring back Recycler
  12. Recycler sends Harp Horror (Note: If one of your recycler targets has ended up in the GY through other means, you can send a skeleton at this point instead)

At this point you can either go into a 3 or 4 material Appolousa (depending on if Wyvern's still here), or another link-4, and use Lib's GY effect to shuffle an opponent's card away, then follow up with Orcust plays, but if we're going first I prefer to instead use Harp to summon Knightmare, link her + Golem into Galatea, Wand summons Harp, Galatea sets Babel, Knightmare sends Skeleton to GY, Overlay Galatea into Dingirsu and attach Knightmare, then link Dingirsu + Scrap Recycler into I:P Masquerena so you can go into a 2-3 material Appolousa (or other link-4) on your opponent's main phase, once they've played a card you want to shuffle away with Lib. We also have a skeleton in the GY that can bring back Dingirsu to send an opposing monster to GY (without targeting!) should it be necessary.

Alternatively, if you haven't done full combo, ending on Galatea + Masq with babel up lets you make a bomber dragon on opponent's turn and then use orcusts in GY to summon something into its zone and blow up the board. If you're really feeling spicy you can make a bomber dragon while Dingirsu is out and has material on it, using its destruction protection to only explode your opponent's field.

Another fun little technique is to use Knightmare during opponent's turn to send world wand and give Apollousa another 800atk, which gives her an extra negate. You can also use Knightmare as a combat trick during the damage step.

Oh yeah and the reason Wind Pegasus @Ignister is in the extra deck is for when you open scrap raptor with recycler already in hand, you can get scrap factory instead and then when wyvern pops you can summon an extra scrap raptor from deck (make sure wyvern is CL1 and factory CL2, then pop factory with wyvern cause you won't need it any more) and synchro wind pegasus with raptor + recycler later down the line (before you go into your link-4 or orcust plays). Feel free to swap it out for a knightmare cerberus or some other link monster you like if that feels like overkill (it is (but it's funny)).

Also, you can swap Borreload Dragon for Avramax if you'd prefer. I don't have him.

The Danger!?s exist as extenders if you get negated and sometimes, if you're lucky, they will unbrick a hand where you drew world wand or something. Mostly I just think they're cute, and a good way to get extra bodies on the field for link plays. You can also use Nessie as part of this package if you're feeling spicy. But honestly you could probably cut the Danger!s out for more handtraps and a 3rd raptor, if you want.

Speaking of handtraps, replacing the effect veilers with more copies of maxx c, ash, imperm, or adding crossout designator is probably worth doing if you can, but I don't own more copies of those cards because I'm a freak who keeps spending her crafting points on stupid sh*t instead of rounding out her collection of staples.

Finally, if you really want to have the Optimal Deck Size (truly enlightened players recognise that the optimal deck size is in fact 41-44. I will not be answering questions about this.) you can cut one of the orcustrated returns. I like running 2 because it can be a pseudo-opener or extender and/or unbrick bad hands.

Enjoy, and may your opponent's Ash remain firmly out of their opening draw.
FIRE FIST
Joyous Melffy Spright By: YII

deck_excerpt: Who knew spirits XYZ was a thing
deck_description:
Inspired by a gamer in the ocg running Sakitama in Exosisters. The main part of the deck is the fact you wont be Normal Summoning much besides your Spirits or Time Thief Regulator .

Aratama will be doing most of the cleansing here by fetching your Spirit Monsters, Nikitama helps him by giving an extra summon for your spirits and the new Sakitama gives you a summon of a Spirit by revealing itself. Now what you can search of Aratama is wild, Rasetsu is a Neo-Spacian Grand Mole by revealing a Spirit in hand, the infamous Tsukuyomi which can Book of Moon upon its summon, Yamato-no-Kami which can banish a Spirit from GY to SS itself to your field, this card is mostly a play for your Bystials to make Wollow, Founder of the Drudge Dragons , Hebo, Lord of the River which can turn any monster into a spirit for Endphase Compulsory Evacuation Device , Fenghuang which is a nuke for backrow, Yamata Dragon a draw 5 if you inflict battle damage which can also be searched by the Bystials, and finally the holographic rare (did I mention this card is holographic rare?) MrBig Bungus Beatstick himself Sword Emperor - Tsumuhakutsunagi who like most spirits in this deck are here for why not reasons.

You have the basic Bystial Gang 3x Bystial Magnamhut , 2x Bystial Druiswurm and 1x Bystial Baldrake , and a Time Thief Engine, Time Thief Regulator can kickstart your plays by summoning Time Thief Winder ,which can add himself, and another Thief from your deck if you control no monsters, Winder can also Det materials from your Xyzs to summon himself, and Time Thief Bezel Ship can steal stuff from your Opponent's GY, Kagetokage will be always on because you will be normal summoning, Performage Hat Tricker can SS himself if you control 2 monsters while Abyss Actor - Curtain Raiser when you dont control monsters. 

Now for the Gem-Knight Garnet we have a lot of those here... Exosister Kaspitell searches Exosister Elis which can summon herself if you control an Exosister, Tellarknight Constellar Caduceus can banish Constellar Sheratan to search Constellar Caduceus which can special summon himself to get Tellarknight Constellar to make Stellarknight Constellar Diamond which floodgates and negates the GY and Dark Monsters respectively (this should be used in the end of a combo otherwise you will lock yourself), Number 39: Utopia Double can search Double or Nothing! (which you wont use unless you go into utopia) and then Rank-Up into Number 99: Utopia Dragonar which summons Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy which is a Spell negator and Attack redirector, Springans Merrymaker which can send Springans Rockey to the GY overlay into Gigantic "Champion" Sargas to then search Therion "King" Regulus which can equip the Rockey. And you have Infinitrack Fortress Megaclops and Number F0: Utopic Draco Future .

This deck is by no means Meta, its a funny thing you can play casually with friends and peep into the horror of generic rank 4 monsters, if konami gave me more 5 ED slots I would have added the Scrap engine, Clownblade, Reptiles and Sprights somehow into it.

This is a combo if you open, Winder, Curtain, Saki and Hat tricker:

Curtain Raiser Pend Effect > SS itself, Sakitama Summons itself from hand, overlay into Exosister Caspitelle > Det for Elis > Elis SS herself, Hat Tricker SS himself, Time Thief Winder Target Exo det material to SS himself + Add Ship, TellarConst Caduceus, effect send sheratan add Caduceus, Caduceus SS and add TellarConst, make merrymaker which sends rocky, overlay it into sargas and add regulus, regulus SS himself by targeting rockey, TellarConst Makes Diamond, If your opponent doesnt have a monster this is your endboard I think, if they do go into infinitrack and steal their monster and bring back Diamond, or you can not summon merrymaker and go into the utopia double route, Double > searches Double or nothing > Dragonar > Hope Harbinger
For my Arc-V OC

Deck Ishizu/Naturia/Vernusylph for the MAMA format . Deck take advantage of the fact Tear/Ishizu is tier 0 by not having any target for the Bystial that are rampant in the format and who are the main hand trap played right now. Also neither Naturia Camellia nor the Vernusylph card target so you don't suffer from shufflers as much as a lot of other deck and you contest those shufflers with your own. You also can take advantage of your opponent milling you with card like the shufflers , Naturia Mole Cricket and Naturia Sacred Tree .

 

You also have strong knockout card against a variety of match-up.

 Gravekeeper's Trap + Exchange of the Spirit against Tear and other GY reliant deck

True King Lithosagym, the Disaster is also basically an FTK against Tear if it resolves

Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir + Naturia Bamboo Shoot against Floowandereeze

Naturia Beast is a killer against any spell based strategie , mainly Runick this format

Naturia Barkion is great against Labyrinth

 

As far as combo goes , Cricket is a 1 card Naturia Beast + Naturia Mole Cricket

Since Naturia Blessing summon from hand AND GY and doesn't target , you can use it to summon from hand and send both it and a naturia monster you want to summon to GY with Forbidden Droplet  for 2 negates + 1 Naturia monster special summon

Forbidden Droplet and Gravekeeper's Trap are also very usefull to send dead card in hand like Naturia Sacred Tree or Exchange of the Spirit to the GY and get their effect

Gravekeeper's Trap can get you to ANY Vernusylph monster which make Mudora the Sword Oracle way more powerfull in this deck than in any other

Finally Vera is a very good boss monster , monster she steal stay on your field , she can use her effect to spe an earth monster for insane target like Barrier Statue of the Drought or a spend Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir AND her monster effect negation activate during resolution , so you if you manage to get to 5 earth monster during the chain (with Naturia Blessing or Agido hand effect for exemple ) you can negate DURING the resolution
Slap them cheeks

Hi all,

A little Despia deck today, with a little chips in it. 
Despite of the Bystials in the format and their missing in this decklist, I believe Despia to stay a strong archetype in the Meta. Morover, I really enjoy playing Despia and I love the Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer card. And fortunately, this card is playable in Despia!

 

How to Improve the Deck (without removing DPE)?

  • Adding Bystials (1 The Bystial Lubellion, 2 Bystial Magnamhut and 1 Bystial Druiswurm is a good choice IMO)
  • Garura, Wings of Resonant Life instead of Mudragon of the Swamp
  • Some changes in the Side Deck for stronger power cards (like Evenly Matched for exemple)
  • Overall, there are some reworks in the Main deck (one more Allure of Darkness, one more Tri-Brigade Mercourier), but it's more about your preferences.

As usual, if you have any suggestions/feedbacks, do not hesitate to share it :)

This deck is made primarily from 2x Albaz strike and a couple of extra cards that are considered the most crucial for the budget version of the branded archetype. Though far from meta-level, I have had it tested a dozen times to see its consistency, and it could play through some interruptions when going second and could easily get to Mirrorjade + another fusion going first.

I am not one for detailed outline of how this deck works but the general flow (depending on the hand and interruptions you might get):

- Set up at least to Mirrorjade and preferably either masquerade or Despian Quaeritis (either through Aluber's effect and aim for branded fusion or through using Albaz's effect and fuse with an opponent's monster. If possible, kaiju the opponent first). When using branded fusion, use ad libitum as the other material, so you could make use of his recycle effects later on.

- Summon sequence: Lubellion -> Albion -> Mirrorjade, then set up for either Masquerade or Quaeritis with the remainder in your hand.

- If your monsters are disrupted, aim to recycle for Mirrorjade by searching for branded in red and target albaz or aluber again. Then chain this effect with the banished ad libitum (from using Albion's effect)  you can search branded fusion again and chain it with ad libitum's effect to special summon Mirrorjade again.

- Other strats in a pinch: stall the opponent with Dimensional Barrier, the Artifact strategy, DRNM or worse yet; TCBOO (after you've made a safety net for yourself).

There are plenty of other players who've made a more detailed description of this archetype, but at least I would like to share my list for the cheapest set up I could think of (sadly, no ash...). Cards that you could add to increase the consistency further: 1x Branded fusion, 3x Branded opening (but not in this list due to the price at the moment) and 1x branded in red. Of course, ash too if you have them already or can afford them. So far, I could hold up fairly well in my locals.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

*Columns exist* Yes... It's MEKKIN TIME!!!!!

This classic 5 year old blind second deck still can smash it's way through current meta, especially in Masterduel's latest event - THEME CHRONICLE!!!

No in-depth explanation for this decklist, Mekk-Knights are fairly straight forward and already figured out. :)

Clear your opponent's board to create a simplified gamestate with this deck's many boardbreakers, then methodically force a grind game with Mekk-Knight's swarm, beatdown and resource gathering ability. This is mainly done with the 10 searchers this deck has access to, that being Mekk-Knight Purple Nightfall, Blue-Sky, Orcust Girsu, and World Legacy's Memory.

Hard-to-out extra deck bosses are usually the win condition in this deck, like a I:P Masquereena boosted Avramax, an untargetable/undestroyable Mekk-Knight Spectrum Supreme or the column-dependent battle phase champion Mekk-Knight Morning Star.

In a simplified gamestate vacuum, Mekk-Knight Avramax is nigh-unkillable and often is a "checkmate" on your opponent. Zeus can also be used comfortably in this deck, enabled by easy access to Mekk-Knight Orcust Girsu -> Galatea -> Dingirsu.

deck_excerpt: macro monarch, teamdrawphase, competitive deck profile, master duel, chronicle theme, master duel event, event meta,
deck_description:
Bringing back the OG!

Macro Monarchs is a unique and powerful deck that utilizes Dimensional Fissure and Macro Cosmos to inhibit the opponent's ability to use their graveyard, which is a crucial resource for many popular decks. Dimensional Fissure and Macro Cosmos work together to banish all cards from both players' graveyards, making it difficult for the opponent to use graveyard-dependent cards, effects, and strategies.

The deck's main win condition is to protect Dimensional Fissure and Macro Cosmos in order to continue banishing cards and disrupt the opponent's gameplay. To achieve this, the deck employs a range of support cards such as D.D. Survivor and D.D. Scout. These cards have effects that activate in the banished zone, which allows them to "infinitely" revive monsters and maintain a strong board presence.

In addition to these support cards, the deck also utilizes the powerful monarchs: Cauis, Raiza, and Mobius. These cards provide a range of effects that help to clear the opponent's board, set up bricks, and hit backrow, which can be a prevalent issue in Master Duel.

I personally have had great success with this deck, going 10-0 in matches against top tier decks such as Crusadia and Beetrooper. This deck not only offers a high level of competitiveness but also offers a budget-friendly option as it does not require the use of the Extra Deck in most cases.

Overall, Macro Monarchs is a well-rounded deck that offers a unique and effective strategy for disrupting the opponent's graveyard-dependent gameplay. I highly recommend giving this deck a try for players who are looking for a strong and budget-friendly option.

How This Deck Works

deck_excerpt: This is not only a control deck, not only an OTK deck, it is the most versatile deck you will ever play. Auto win on basically any match up.
deck_description:
The main goal of the deck is to see atleast clockwork night and one cyber dragon. However if you do see clockwork and rivalry and your opponent has no spell or traps to remove it, you basically auto win. Once these two cards are on the field together your opponent gets one summon then they are locked into machines, if they don't already have mosnters on the board. If they do already have mosnters than they immediately are locked out of playing anything except machine monsters which about 1% of decks can play through. If they do have any sort of removal for your floodgates you should already have an Omni negate set up if not two of them, seeing as you consistently see the combo pieces to either make infinity turn one or regulis turn one.

The reason why this deck is the most versatile and best for every match up, is because any cyber dragon + clockwork = contact fuse of your opponent's entire board. I have successfully contact fused a full 6 card tear board on turn two with literally two cards, putting my fortress dragon at 7500 atk and needing one more decent size monster to win the game. Also the combination of floodgates I have chosen has made it almost impossible for any deck to play except for mine.

So my thinking here is pretty standard on most fronts.

I don't have and cannot afford the big money staples that should go here, and I'd add if I could.

Baronne de Fleur, Triple Tactics Talent, Foridden Droplet, the Bystial monsters.

I've tried to mix up my side deck and main deck so I can swap out between interuptions and board breaks depending on going first/second. I think I'd always keep Effect Veiler in for the additional tuner.

The two tech cards I've put in that I've not seen to often is Instant Fusion, the Magikey and Golden Sarc. Idea here is that if MoYe token summon is negated I could either Instant Fusion a tuner to the field and continue to play, or golden sarc one of the blackouts for a token. 

I see most decks run one Blackout - I run two because I run Prosperity and also for the Gold Sarc target. 

 

I'm returning after a long time out - I'd love to hear any thoughts on this budget build. The handtraps in the side and main can always be switched out depending on the current meta. But I think this would be a fairly solid deck, and could do well at locals - possibly higher.

deck_excerpt: Play when opponent plays and play more after you disrupt them!
deck_description:
Inspiration from:  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tkH9NAe842g&ab_channel=Poofadoof
Possibly the 2nd melffy ghoti deck out there xD

Play style:

This deck plays heavily in your opponents turn doing synchro plays, building your own resources while interupting your opponent all at the same time.

 

The core idea of this deck is to bring out Arionpos, the lv6 ghoti and start the ghoti combo while getting more resources through melffy stuff.

Both melffy and ghoti speciallize in playing during your opponents turn. Ghoti can perform quick synchros when ss and melffies can search out Pinny and Hop ear to achieve the same. Due to the nature of banish + next turn plays of the ghoti and the many numbers of melffy, the deck can play through and around quite a few handtraps/negates. Crossout is a extremly useful interupt and extender/starter that works the same as gold sarcophagus.

Melffy Wally, Puppy, Lifeless leafish are all 1 card starters.

The melffies can be used to search out pinny or hop ear and both their effects trigger in hand. depending on the opening hand you can usually have 1 banish from Askaan. And could go into 4-6-8-10 synchro climb while using melffies to pop/bounce and banish/board wipe with fish, providing a lot of interaction during your opponents turn. with muliple melffies you can also chain block to protect catty's effect, grating at least a lv 4 syncho with Pinny.

The 3 evil hero cards are used as back up when the opening hand isnt great, ss evil hero, normal summon any lv2 in hand xyz into Melffy of the Forest and search Puppy or Wally to start, these can then search more melffies in your opponents turn and gather enough resources to perfrom synchros. Melffy Fenny is a extra search target when you got catty/puppy + wally in hand

Other options:

dream shark is searchable through Arionpos' float effect and can be used to go into the lv7 white aura synchro which can then revive a fish tuner in the gy and go into any lv9 synchro, in this case shenshen for more interuption, but the combo isnt very consistent because dream sharks summon condition but a good option if you start with only fish. Baronne is a generic good option, but chengying and rudy rose feel better in this deck. Chengying has a natural synergy with the ghoti's heavy banish focus and Rudy rose is a good way to clean your opponents gy while setting your own ghotis and pumping Chengying and Deep Beyond's atk for a potential otk

The hand traps are all generic space and can be replaced with anything

The deck could work well with Sprights and could use a bystial or fenrir package but out of personal preference I did not add them in. 

Feel free to experiment and provide feed back <3

deck_name: Destiny HERO Deck List & Combo Post 2023 New Years
deck_description:
This Destiny HERO deck focuses on preventing the opponent from using their own spell cards with Destiny HERO - Dark Angel and Rivalry of Warlords. This is a the legal version of Imperial Order. 

Combo

Hand

  • Fusion Destiny

  • Rivalry of Warlords

Board

  • Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer

  • Destiny HERO - Dark Angel (On The Opponent's Side Of The Field)

  • Rivalry of Warlords

Notes

  • All spell cards the opponent activates are negated and destroyed. 

  • The opponent cannot get rid of Destiny HERO - Dark Angel by normal means. Rivalry of Warlord limits the type of monsters your opponent can use. 
  • Destiny HERO - Malicious will be shuffled back into the deck for other combos that can be used later on. Destiny HERO - Malicious only uses its own effect once during this combo. 

Steps

  1. Activate Fusion Destiny to fusion summon Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer (Destiny HERO - Malicious + Destiny HERO - Denier). 
  2. Banish Destiny HERO - Malicious from the graveyard to special summon its copy from the deck. 
  3. Since you control a Destiny HERO monster on the field, special summon Destiny HERO - Denier from the graveyard by its own effect. Then activate its other effect to put the banished Destiny HERO - Malicious on top of the deck. 
  4. Link summon into Xtra HERO Cross Crusader (Destiny HERO - Malicious + Destiny HERO - Denier) into the extra monster zone.
  5. Activate Xtra HERO Cross Crusader, special summon Destiny HERO - Malicious from the graveyard. 
  6. Activate Xtra HERO Cross Crusader's other effect, tribute Destiny HERO - Malicious to search Destiny HERO - Dark Angel. 
  7. Activate Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer, destroyer itself and Xtra HERO Cross Crusader if your opponent doesn't have a card on their side of the field to destroy.
  8. Since Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer, Destiny HERO - Malicious, and Destiny HERO - Denier is in the graveyard, activate Destiny HERO  - Dark Angel to special summon this monster to the opponent's side of the field. 
  9. Set Rivalry of Warlords. 
  10. During the opponent's standby phase, activate Rivalry of Warlords and return Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer to your side of the field. 

Top Cards To Banish For Pot Of Prosperity

  • Destiny HERO - Dangerous
  • Masked HERO Anki
  • Masked HERO Divine Wind
  • Elemental HERO The Shining
  • Elemental HERO Escuridao
  • Xtra HERO Wonder Driver

deck_excerpt: Morphtronic, Power Tool, Non Meta, Pure
deck_description:
It's Morphtronics! They are kinda difficult to build in a pure way even with all the support they got. This List is made from many years of experience with this Archetype in a way to get the most out of many different Morphtronics with the additional Focus on their Boss Monster Power Tool Dragon. Let's go into Detail: 

 

The Power Tool Path

In general your focus should be to Build up a Power Tool Dragon or the new Braver Dragon as soon as possible and they are not only great Beatsticks with some Tower Functions. They can also get out the Equip Spells from your Deck fast and make your whole Deck more Consistent.

2 Power Tool Dragons equipped with their Equip Spell Double Tool C & D can create a perfect attack Wall while guarding themselves from destruction and negating any effect of Monsters they Battle with 3300 ATK. Note that the C & D equip is only usable on the OG Power Tool Dragon or a Morphtronic Machine Monster with LV4 or Higher.

Power Tool Braver Dragon is missing the protection, that's why you play the Supermagic Sword Raptinus to make up for that. That card feels like written for Morphtronics since it can also change Battle Positions and give an additional Normal Summon. Extreme Life is obviously there to make use of Bravers own negation/battle position change effect to get out Lifestream Dragon, or to just be a imaginary 4k Beater with Card destruction Ability. 

At first sight Power Pickaxe looks like a strange addition but think a moment about it. You can use the effect to Banish a Monster from the opponents GY and gain 500 ATK first and then use Bravers effect to get rid of the Equip Spell for his own effect. Maximum Advantage to be made right there.

The Power Tool Mecha Dragons can facilitate additional Draw Power if needed. The Lifestream Dragon is useful if many Equip Spells are already in the GY and/or your Life Points are very low. A very good backup Card. 

The one who combines them all is Ultimaya Tzolkin. You will need Lifestream Dragon to summon him in this Deck but once there he can easily summon one Power Tool Monster every turn and get targeting protection too. He even summons Power Tool Braver Dragon and triggers his effect. 

To end this Paragraph see the Power Tools as your Main way to get your Deck going up to speed. They are very important for the Morphtronic Strategy.

 

The Morphtronics arrive

To even summon Power Tool Boss Monsters you need the help of the Consistency bringers, the Morphtronics. They each have a different Effect based on their current Battle Position. There are numerous ways to get to Level 4, 7, 8 and 9 in this Deck and it's a bit up to luck too. 

Your 3 different Level 1 Telephones bring the Main Search and Summon Power for this Deck. Morphtronic Converter a powerful Spell helps to set up these Monsters and their effects. They require a Die Roll which makes their effects a little luck based but they are all soft once per turns making big Combos very easy.

But that's not all! The Scannen can search for Spells & Traps, while the Scopen can set up a instant level 7 Synchro summon. Remoten also has applications in that area. 

And that's still not all. There's also Gadgets which support this Archetype. Gadget Gamer being the best one, again setting up for a L7 Synchro Summon and searching your Level 1 Starters. Gadget Box is always treated as Morphtronic Card and is easy to access through Scannen and is basically an additional L1 special summon every turn in form of a Token.

With all these tools you will be easily summoning multiple Power Tool Monsters in one turn. But what if I tell you that's not the only way to go? 

 

The Morphtronics Strike Back!

Now with all this Consistency it's obvious you will have Space for another Main Deck Strategy. The Direct Attack OTK! Morphtronic Boarden allows every Morphtronic to attack directly. Boomboxen can attack twice and is a legal target for the equip C & D and Radion is a 800 ATK Boost for all Morphtronics. The Field Spell is another 300 ATK on top, every time you change a Battle Position. 

With all that said it's very easy to reach 8000 total Damage through direct attacks to OTK the opponent. When the opponent is to focused on your Power Tool Boss Monsters surprise him with this Backup Plan. This is also highly effective to get past unbeatable Towers and win like that and it's easy to set up within one turn too.

 

Additional Spice is always good

So the Telefon FTK is well known but not part of this pure Variant... BUT Morphtronic Clocken can Deal 1000 DMG by tributing itself (Or more if you wait many turns) and you can loop that effect a few times too. All depends on you rolling a 2 or Higher and having the means to re summon Telefon and Clocken multiple times. Convoluted for sure but effective nontheless. It does make the Direct attack OTK even more dangerous. 

The new Trap Impact Return is a quick effect Speed reborn from the GY or the Banished pile and can shuffle back S & Ts from the opponent on activation. This card is 110% useful I can't even explain it all here. 

Staplen can create a Attack Wall like C & D when combined in any way you desire. One Staplen and one C & D = Attack Wall. Slingen is a little Removal Tool. Earfon is the L4 Synchro useful in many Situations, especially to use Braver Dragons effect many times.

 

So it's the best Deck ever right? 

No not at all. All these Combos described can be easily stopped with all the usual stuff like Nibiru and Floodgates. Having to rely and Die Rolls and having some weird downsides/costs on some cards make this Deck miss the Mark to reach the Overpowered territory. It's a Combo Deck in it's Core. 

 

Final Words

Morphtronics are fun. You have many possible Combinations within this Deck and can surprise your opponent with unusual ways and Cards. Try this Deck if you like bigger Combo Decks that aren't super complicated to understand. I really liked them ever since their Anime Debut and maybe you too will find them to be fun to play^^ 

Overall Rating: ★★★★☆☆

deck_excerpt: A mid-range Ghoti deck focused on consistently setting up a Askaan/Aura Whale -> Big Ghoti -> another Askaan/Aura Whale
deck_description:
You try to make Arionpos as soon as possible, with both Shif and Paces banished. That results in one Askaan -> Big Ghoti on your opponents turn. If you have either Snopios or Zep in your hand you can also summon a White Aura Whale afterwards. I am not a fan of the combo-on-your-own-turn-with-Coelecanth-variant, as Big Ghoti also banishes your own cards, and then all the cool set-up would go to waste.

Shif is the best of the Ghoti Tuners due to being able to banish itself from the GY. Paces is probably the worst one, as it cannot banish itself from the GY, only from field. Zep only works when banished on your opponents turn, which is good and bad. Ixeep summons itself when added by the Field Spell, similar to Salamangreat Gazelle. Snopios is very good, as it can add itself back to hand. Eanoc is bad, same for the traps.

Lifeless Leaffish can either set up White Mirror or send Shif so you can banish it and make Arionpos -> Askaan/Whale on your opponents turn (via Zep). Silent Angler is just an easy extender, but be careful with it's summonlock. Beautunaful Princess get's you any fish you want/need and is summonable with One for One.

Supay is really good, as it get's you any Lv. 6 Synchro, which is nbasically all you want to do turn 1.

White Mirror is an insanely good card, a perfect extender that also gets you follow-up. The fieldspell is also really good and does basically anything the deck wants.

Arionpos banishes you either your tuners, or you can banish Snopios, banish a tuner from GY and then add Snopios to hand. It also searches you any fish by banishing a fish with same or lower level when it is used as Synchromaterial. Askaan usually banishes itself and an opponents card, and then it can come back. it revives itself no matter from where it is banished, so you can revive it on your turn again with e.g. Snopios. Big Ghoti is insane. Just banish everything and then hit your opponent for like 5000 ATK. Guoglim is... really bad. There are some set-ups with it when you have Arionpos + a Tuner on your turn. But it's better to just make Dragite. White Aura Whale is... insane. You Lightning-Storm your opponent, do piercing on 2 monsters, and revive yourself... without a OPT. But be careful, the on-summon effect can miss timing. Chengying is a good Lv. 10 to make on your own turn, as you bansih a lot, so you can easily trigger it and reduce the stats of opponents cards by a lot. Stardust Charge is there because sometimes you need to clean up a board of a lot of small monsters, and you sometimes need another Lv. 6 Synchro. Keeper and Cerberus are there to out e.g. Bagooska.

Play handtraps/staples at your own leisure.

The deck is surprisingly good, and I think whis is the way to play it atm. But we need an additional wave of good Ghoti cards so that it becomes really good. The cards are often in their own way and underpowered (e.g. Zep can banish itself from hand and one fish from your GY, but not as a quick effect. Shifs ATK boost is SS1 and only until end of turn, etc.). So I hope we get more cards for them

deck_excerpt: The mighty Rank 10 Trains! Here's my list, as well as an extensive, in depth guide on how to play the deck! CHOO CHOO!
deck_description:
This is the build of Rank 10 Trains (AKA Earth Machine) that I've used to make it all the way to Platinum on Master Duel. 

OVERVIEW:  Rank 10 Trains is a beatdown deck that's main gameplan is to rely on sheer brute force and is capable of achieving easy OTK's as early as turn 1! The deck is very simple to pick up and play, but is very difficult to fully master. Games with Trains almost never last more than a few turns, making it the perfect deck to use for ladder climbing. 

GOING FIRST:  If you're on the play, your gameplan is to always summon Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora ASAP. 

With Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora you have what many duelists consider to be the "true Boss Monster" of the archetype. Juggernaut may be the win condition, but Number 81 is your true workhorse and backbone. Under most normal circumstances, you almost always want to summon Number 81 in Defense Mode if you're going first. 

What makes Number 81 so dangerous as an opening lead is it's resiliance and Spell Speed 2 ability to react to the opponent and bunker itself in and become a truly unkillable monster. Number 81's ability gives it an immunity to literally every single effect. 

How can we abuse this to our advantage? With Heavy Freight Train Derricrane of course! Derricrane is the linchpin to the deck. Combined with the Quick Effects of Number 81, detaching Derricrane gives you some reactionary spell speed 2 destruction. A single well timed Number 81 + Derricrane can criple an enemy's combo. And now you're pulling WAY ahead with an unkillable 4000 DEF wall. 

To give yourself an even bigger, backbreaking disruptive advantage; we have one of the most useful and underrated Trap cards at our disposal: Spin Turn! 

If Spin Turn is in your opening hand, summon your Number 81 in ATK Mode, so we can make full use of Spin Turn. Also, if you plan on using Spin Turn, make sure to activate Spin Turn before activating Number 81. This way you can swap 81 into defense mode before it becomes immune to all effects. 

GOING SECOND: When Trains are on the draw, they become one of the most lethal and consistent OTKs in the game. 

Under normal circumstances, our gameplan is to present a turn 1 kill. Summon Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max. Activate it's effect to cause 2000 damage. Then rank it up into our ULTIMATE Monster! Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe!
Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe can make itself into a 6000 ATK monstrosity. And 2000 + 6000 = Checkmate.

However, most competent opponents will be aware of our full throttle assault. As powerful and as lethal as Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe is, it has no protection. A well timed Trap Card or Quick Effect can stop Juggernaut from ending the game. 
This is especially true the higher up the ranks you get. So now we have to get creative and position our pieces correctly. 

Usually to prevent such a blowout from a sneaky Mirror Force, we again will be relying on our good friend Heavy Freight Train Derricrane. Who I implore you to always hook up Derricrane to your Gustav Max, because now your 2000 point explosion can double as removal. Blasting away our opponent's defenders and back row. 

I still recommend, if given the choice, that you decide to go first, because having the constant threat of Number 81 is much better for you long term than going for an instant going second OTK. 

Because, who said we couldn't go for our big swinging OTK on our next turn? With all our pieces in place, and our early game interaction courtesy of Number 81 and Spin Turn. We can now use the rest of our resources organizing a counter attack and mollywhopping our opponent with the big bad Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe! 

THE INFINITRACK ENGINE: Infinitracks are our engine to make our Trains go ham. If you don't have both Derricrane and another level 10 Train in your oppening hand. You almost always have one of our plethora of Infinitrack searchers. 

The proper combo line is to use Infinitrack Harvester as our Normal Summon (if you don't have both Night Express Knight and Heavy Freight Train Derricrane in your opening hand).
Harvester will search for Infinitrack Brutal Dozer.  Tribute your Harvester and special summon Brutal Dozer. Now use Dozer to grab either Infinitrack Tunneller or Infinitrack Trencher. It's usually correct to grab Trencher first. You should only be grabbing Tunneller if you know for a fact that the game will go very long and your opponent has cards like Nibiru or Infinite Impermanence in their hand. However, both work the same for our combo so it's usually up to preference which you want to use first. 

Now with 2 level 5 machines in play, we can XYZ summon our premier searcher. Infinitrack River Stormer! River Stormer can easily grab whichever Level 10 monster we need. 

Other cards to further give us what we need are Revolving Switchyard and Urgent Schedule  

 Heavy Forward should normally be used to search for Infinitrack Harvester, but Heavy Forward also makes for an awesome tool to bait out an Ash Blossom. 

Now that all the pieces are in place. Quickly equip Heavy Forward to your Number 81 as an extra XYZ material. Because having 3 XYZ Material on Number 81 is way more important than people realize.

LATE GAME:  The late game should be spent being belligerent and using your massive Trains to trample over your opponent's monsters. 

An interesting quirk I've noticed about modern Yu-Gi-Oh cards is that less and less monsters are being printed with the "can't be destroyed by battle" ability. Which we can use to our advantage, and for the monsters in the game that can't be destroyed by battle? Don't worry! Most boss monster ATK points cap at 3000, while yours can reach numbers quadruple that!

What makes Trains so enjoyable is that you very rarely have to worry about opposing boss monster special abilities that prevent them from being targeted or destroyed by effects. All you need to do is make a big train with more than 3k atk and crash into everything. Popular decks like Dragon Maids, Blue-Eyes, Red-Eyes, Thunder Dragons, Adamancipators, Sky Strikers, Odd-Eyes and Dark Magicians simply cannot face Trains in a head to head battle. Our ability to protect ourselves from all their card effects with Number 81, and then be able to also create monsters bigger than anything their decks can present gives us an edge that other decks are struggling to achieve. 

And for the few rare cases where a monster becomes bigger than our Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe? That's where our tech cards come into play. Book of Moon is my favorite tool to suppress big threats. Because these few decks that're built on the idea of being bigger than our monsters don't have much defense points, nor do their abilities stop us from using Book of Moon to criple them. 

If you're terrified of floating effects, do not fret, as we have both Infinitrack River Stormer and Infinitrack Earth Slicer to gobble up their freshly destroyed monsters.

And if all else fails, Trains has the ultimate contingency plan: Infinitrack Fortress Megaclops! Which is by a mile our most unstoppable force. 
Boss Monsters may be immune to destruction, but not Megaclops's rare ability to absorb enemies and transform them into more Trains! 

If things are going well for us, Megaclops gives us the ultimate failsafe.

CONCLUSION: Trains is by no means perfect. It has a massive trouble against Kaijus and can't compete with decks that focus on nothing but early game disruption. It also does not like cards that manipulate attributes because it requires such a high volume of Earth Machines. It also can't afford to cut core cards because it requires such a high density of specific machines to make the deck work. So it is very hard to find room for cards that Trains desperately want to use. 

The Sideboard is full cards that I believe can remedy these weaknesses as best as we can. 

Train Connection : Useful as an extra way to beat over problem boss monsters who think they can grow bigger than Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe, hooking Juggernaut up with a Train Connection makes Juggernaut capable of hitting for 16000ATK! And I guaruntee you, NOTHING is beating over that. 

Barrage Blast : Useful as mass removal. As after a successful set-up, we'll have plenty of leftover XYZ material that we don't need. We can use these as ammo for a late game finishing Barrage Blast! 

Outrigger Extension : Perfect way to give us some early game protection, probably most useful against Eldlich and other control decks.

Crusher Run : A card I adore. It's useful to punish greedy opponents who aim to use removal effects. An "Eye for an Eye" if you will

Mystical Space Typhoon : For those games when just 1 or 2 Derricranes aren't enough to break all the backrow. Another card that's useful against Trap based control decks. 

Solemn Judgment : The defacto big hard NO. Much like Ash Blossom, it's usefulness doesn't need much explanation

Infinitrack Mountain Smasher : A solid beatstick with that wonderful absorbing effect to gobble up monsters we destroy so they can't be used for our opponent's GY abilities. I personally think it's a bit of a noob trap, but it can be very useful for those unlucky games where you brick and have the wrong pieces and are in desperate need of getting an XYZ monster in play to get the ball rolling

Double Headed Anger Knuckle : Another card I've used religiously over the years. This little guy can easily turn clunky brick hands into total gas! Anger Knuckle is also an awesome tool to make a comeback from Kaijus. Simply ditch a brick, scoop up Derricrane, and now we're cooking! If you can find a way to fit Anger Knuckle into your extra deck, please do! His lategame utility is awesome!
BURN

R-ace, Purrely and Mikanko's weird brother, a control playstyle focused on Fire Machine/Warrior monsters that use from Quickplays and Traps to stop your opponent on their tracks and swarm the field with their on-hand effects that activate in response to monster effects.

The main man in the deck is the unassuming Rescue-ACE Hydrant , a LV1 monster that allows you to get imediate use from the cards set by their other important monster Rescue-ACE Turbulence and it can add any of your monsters from your deck to hand, this guy is important for their S/T, so important in fact some builds use Gizmek Naganaki, the Sunrise Signaler to summon him from your deck, but I chose not to because the other monsters can fetch him from your deck if you really need to in addition to One for One and Pot of Prosperity His level also means Linkuriboh is a viable card in the deck.

Rescue-ACE Turbulence on the other hand for the low price of banishing any two of your R-ace cards in your grave can special summon itself and set 4 differently named R-ace S/T, which get different effects if our little boy Rescue-ACE Hydrant is on the field, RESCUE! can summon one of your dead R-ace or if Hydrant is on the field you can summon one monster in your opponent's GY instead, ALERT! which can add from GY one of your R-ace monsters or if Hydrant is on the field you can add it from your deck instead, CONTAIN! is the negate + stops attacks and if Hydrant is on the field it cant be used for an Extra Deck summon and finally EXTINGUISH! its a pop that Called by the Grave the monster if Hydrant is on the field.

Rescue-ACE Impulse and Rescue-ACE Air Lifter can tribute themselves from the hand or field to summon a Machine type R-ace from your deck and to summon any R-ace from your hand respectively, their unique effect is being able to negate the effect of the monster with highest attack and to search 1 R-ace Spell which in most case you want to fetch their field Rescue-ACE HQ which gives you an extra Normal Summon of a R-ace and recycles the banished/in gy R-ace cards. Rescue-ACE Fire Attacker and Rescue-ACE Fire Engine can SS themselves to the field if a R-ace was summoned, Attacker gives you 2 draws if your opponent adds a card to their hand while engine summons a LV4 or lower R-ace from anywhere.

Now for the tech cards, Prime Planet Paraisos , Kashtira Fenrir and Kashtira Riseheart , Fenrir gives you ways to deal with overwhelming boards and gives you discard fodder, it can also search Rise that can SS itself if you control a Kashtira monster so you can go into a R4NK with your other LV4s, SPYRAL Resort and SPYRAL Super Agent which can be searched with the field to give you another LV4 body. Both of the fields can be activated via Set Rotation or Reinforcement of the Army .

Since the LVs on the deck are weird you only run some R4NKs, Number 39: Utopia Double gives you a massive body with Double or Nothing! and go into Number 99: Utopia Dragonar which in turn summons Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy . Springans Merrymaker to overlay into Gigantic "Champion" Sargas to fetch Therion "King" Regulus which causes the XYZ to become a 4mat Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder .

The new support (REINFORCE!) is unfortunately not what the deck needed and it pales in comparison to Fu-Ri the Orb Mikanko or Purrely Lily , hopefully they will receive some good support in the near future.

deck_excerpt: RESCUE-ACE, THERION, REGULUS, ROGUE, META CONTENDER, UNDERDOG, TEAMDRAWPHASE, DRAW PHASE, PHOTON HYPERNOVA, KASTHIRA, TEARLAMENTS, RUNICK,
deck_description:
The "Rescue-ACE" theme is a control-based deck that centers around its boss monster, "Rescue-ACE Turbulence." This monster has an Ignition Effect that allows it to set up to 4 "Rescue-ACE" Quick-Play Spells and/or Normal Traps directly from the Deck per turn. The other cards in the deck support this card advantage by providing utility, consistency, recovery, and additional swarming options.

The "Rescue-ACE" monster lineup includes Main Deck Machine and Warrior monsters. The Level 3 and 4 Warrior monsters have a Quick Effect that allows them to Tribute themselves from the hand or field to Special Summon a Machine "Rescue-ACE" monster from the hand, GY, or Deck when the opponent activates a Monster effect on the field. The Level 6 and 7 Machine monsters can be Special Summoned from the hand when a "Rescue-ACE" monster is Normal or Special Summoned to the field, other than themselves.

The Deck's secondary key monster is "Rescue-ACE Hydrant," which can actively search for "Turbulence" and has additional self-protection effects. It also enables additional effects for the Deck's Spell/Traps. The theme's Spell and Trap cards provide control, with Quick-Play Spells and Normal Traps having basic supportive/disruptive effects that are enhanced when "Rescue-ACE Hydrant" is on the field. The Field Spell "Rescue-ACE HQ" aids in resource management and monster summoning.

The inclusion of hand traps such as Nibiru, Ash Blossom, and Impermanence helps to control and disrupt the opponent's board. Therion Regulus is included for its synergy with the Machine-type monsters, acting as a free extender and better disruption. The goal of the deck is to control the opponent and beat them down for the win.

Another Simple and Easy to use Warrior Structure Deck I made. 

Even it is not good against meta decks, but still I gave you some referrence to make a descent structure deck.

NOTE Full Going-Second Cydra deck with maximum XYZ outburst and potential, supported with Clockwork Night and Linkuriboh/Almiraj.

Deck choices

Cyber Dragon - Going with 3x because we're looking to maximize Nova-Infinity play and with the addition of Vimana. Surprisingly easy to get both of them out in the same turn, even with Sieger sometimes. A lot of decks run 2x only, but I choose 3 to take advantage of Clockwork Night together with other deck synergies.

Cyber Dragon Core - Easy search and versatility. Its mandatory effect allows to search for other combo-enablers. The GY effect is broken enough on its own (paired with Clockwork Night, as it extends to complete board clear). Usually searching Cyber Emergency, but able to search for Repair Plant as well (if you have the other one in your hand already, as you're only allowed to play one Emergency per turn). Almiraj succeeds in getting rid of it to enable Repair Plant activation, we always want Cyber Dragon(s) in the GY.

Cyber Dragon Herz - I run 3x in a deck without Clockwork, but here, 2x is enough. Send it to the GY for Cyber Dragon search, push for Galaxy Soldier (fastest Nova-Infinity out) and get the omni-negate out. Foolish runs good here if you don't manage to pull Galaxy Soldier in the starting hand.

Galaxy Soldier - 2x is just fine, you don't need 3x. Pair him with Cyber Dragon Herz for search and XYZ summon, not much to say.

Cyber Dragon Nachster - Only one needed. Had to make room for Clockwork, otherwise I'd run 2x at least. Its effect is nifty and allows a bit of tiptoeing around opponent's negates and traps.

Cyber Eltanin - Board wipe, plus you get your machines in banish so you can use with with Cyberload Fusion and/or Overload Fusion for Chimeratech Overdragon.

Ghost Belle - Can be easily swapped with Ash Blossom. I went for 1x Ghost Belle because there's no place for 3x Ash and we want to keep deck at 40.

Jizukiru - Self-explanatory. Also, it's a machine- you're able to contact fuse It. (You can also search it with Repair Plant, just like Galaxy Soldier or Eltanin)

Clockwork Night - Complete board clear. Contact fuse everything they got and get Chimeratech Fortress Dragon with 5000 ATK / 5000 DEF out easily. Therion King Regulus would be a good search for this, but I really don't own him so I've just built a deck around Cyber Dragon(s).

Cyber Emergency - A combo starter if you open with it. Search anything that allows you to combo further.

Machine Duplication - Get your Cyber Dragons out.

Power Bond - Fuse into Chimeratech Rampage Dragon for OTK (or just use its effect to fend off Herz and, usually, Core).

Called by the Grave - Good card if you're going second (even first).

Cyber Repair Plant - Another search for your combo-enablers.

Cyber Revsystem - In case everything else goes wrong, search it with Core and allow yourself another turn to live with contact fusion.

Cyberload Fusion - Polymerization for Cybers.

Foolish Burial - Send Herz (or Cyber Dragon for Nachster target).

Forbidden Chalice - Effect negate.

Instant Fusion - Panzer Dragon and Chimeratech Rampage target (it can still use its effect to send monsters to the GY).

Harpie's Feather Duster - Backrow removal.

Lightning Storm - Removal.

Limiter Removal - OTK potential (you don't need more, you already got Power Bond and multiple attacks with Chimeratech Rampage Dragon).

Monster Reborn

Overload Fusion - Into one of your two DARK machine monsters.

Raigeki - Removal.

Twin Twisters - Backrow removal (plus you get the GY effect from Herz or if you need Cyber Dragon in there, maybe even Core).

Cybernetic Overflow - Excellent card.

Infinite Impermanence - Read the above.

EXTRA DECK

Chimeratech Fortress Dragon - I still think 2x is enough, I wouldn't know what to take out for another one either. In a meta as fast as this, you wouldn't see the light to use the third one at all, 2x is just enough.

Chimeratech Megafleet Dragon - Same as the thing above.

Chimeratech Overdragon - Finisher.

Chimeratech Rampage Dragon - MVP of this deck.

Panzer Dragon - hehe.

Chronomaly Vimana - The only good rank 5 target for your Cybers (since you're not allowed to play 2 Infinities in the same turn).

Cyber Dragon Nova/Infinity

Cyber Dragon Sieger - Great card for boosting ATK in the BP (it's considered as "Cyber Dragon" as well).

Linkuriboh - Get rid of your little Cyber that you have left on the field (or if you need to meet the Repait Plant requirement).

Salamangreat Almiraj - Get rid of your little Cyber that you have left on the field (or if you need to meet the Repait Plant requirement).

SIDE DECK

Contact "C"

Cursed Seal of the Forbidden Spell - You run a lot of spells. Why not?

Cosmic Cyclose - If you need more backrow removal.

Lost Wind - Great card.

Non-Fusion Area - As dumb as it seems, it doesn't screw you over. You XYZ summon anyway, if it's stopping your opponent from playing, you can play off of Vimana-Nova-Infinity as well as your Link.

Shadow-Imprisoning Mirror - For DARK users.

System Down - A lot of consideration went into this one, I just didn't like running it in main deck (even with 3x Clockwork Night in the deck, it just seemed way too unlikely to draw it in your starting hard as well as one of the Clockworks, you have no way for searching either of them out).

Solemn Judgment - If you're really struggling.

Other choices and possibilites

Rivalry of Warlords - Tried it. Too bricky, most of the time you don't even need it.

Of course, you can build a side deck on your own, depending on what you face and play against. I built mine out of cards that I own and that I frequently use against people at locals. Others staples would be favorable.

deck_excerpt: Frusturate your opponent and take advantage of structure decks while utilizing new nightmare link cards with this exciting control deck.
deck_description: The primary goal of this deck is to summon dragon maid sheo on your turn then when the turn is passed to your opponent you can use a combination of dragonmaid sheo and dragonmaid tidying from the graveyard to bring an onslaught of dragonmaid's. hopefully your opponent tries to negate the effect of sheo during the standyphase which allows you to negate using sheos effect then after bringing in house you can summon again during the standby phase as well as having the ability to destroy 1 monster each time a dragonmaid is sent to the hand (which happens once or twice per battle phase per dragonmaid monster). Other than the primary dragonmaid engine this deck is outfitted with enough negation cards to allow the user to block most attempts by the opponent to counter play. This deck is weak to flowandreeze and other decks that banish cards as this deck is heavily reliant on graveyard interaction. Use the link monsters especially hieratic seal in order to put cards in the graveyard so then you can summon more monsters during your opponents turn or your following turn if necessary.

deck_excerpt: Try this "Fun Rogue" deck. it can even fight the META!
deck_description:
Unlike most decks, Runick does not focus on damaging life points, but instead wins by banishing cards off the top of your opponent's deck to force a Deck out. It is composed of LIGHT Fairy and DARK Beast Fusion monsters, most of them have 0 ATK (aside from "Freki the Runick Fangs" who has 2000), but is almost entirely Spell cards, with no Monster Cards or Trap cards in the main deck. The majority of the Runick cards are Quick-Play Spells, which can disrupt the opponent's plays and banish cards off the top of your opponent's deck, or Special Summon one of their Fusion Monsters from the Extra Deck to an unoccupied Extra Monster Zone. However you can only activate each of the Quick-Play Spells once per turn, and are forced to skip your next Battle Phase after they resolve, a drawback that does not negatively impact them greatly as their monsters will never be doing any attacking themselves. Their main card is the Field Spell "Runick Fountain", which they rely on to allow their Quick-Play Spells to be activated from the hand on the opponent's turn and to recycle them, while providing draw power.

All of the "Dogmatika" monsters have effects that counter/disrupt Extra Deck monsters.

Dogmatika will be both deffense as well as board breakers to throw off you OP strategy. 

think of the deck as a Runick deck with teeth. the objesctive is to deck out your OP, but you can fight back if you have to.

 

some kinks still need to be workded out.

deck_excerpt: Clean 40 card mostly pure Harpie deck.
deck_description: Harpie Lady is one of those fair decks that are only able to synchro/XYZ summon one monster per turn, but, at the same time, has access to one of the most broken cards in the game in Harpie's Feather Storm, which, because we actually play Harpies and not some toxic stuff like Floowandereeze, we can activate it from our hand at quick effect speed, meaning that a single Harpie monster can mean stopping the opponent's turn or protecting ourselves from handtraps or being able to break the opponent's field more easily during our turn; we can either hard-draw one of our 3 copies of Feather Storm, set it directly from deck with Trap Trick or search it during the end phase with Hysteric Sign's effect, which is triggered if it's destroyed by something like Harpies' Hunting Ground or by the opponent, or used as cost for something like Forbidden Droplet or Knightmare Phoenix (Remember that Hysteric Sign's search 3 effect can't be used if its effect to search for   Elegant Egotist was activated that turn). Our optimal turn 1 play is the following: Cyber Slash Harpie Lady plus Feather Storm, waiting for the opponent to summon and activate a monster effect and then activating Feather Storm, stopping their monster effects and this way Cyber Slash's effect also activates returning an opponent's monster to the hand, setting them back even further. Our optimal turn 2 plays are the following: with the support from cards like Feather Storm, Feather Duster and Forbidden Droplet, XYZ summon Number 39: Utopia Double to deal up to 10K battle damage on monsters or summon Zoodiac Chakanine into Zoodiac Boarbow to go into a 4 material Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder.

deck_name: Swordsoul Tenyi with a DPE Engine
deck_description:
(Note: Baronne De Fleur makes the deck more optiminal but is not included in this version for budgeting reasons.) 

This is an Average swordsoul tenyi deck. To get an extra negate I run a DPE engine. No hand traps are really run in my version of this deck but can easily be added if you own them.

a lot of these cards are Starters so its very hard to brick. This is my 2nd time doing this deck and I think this is the best possible verion of this deck. each card can pretty much combo into anything you want or need as all extra deck cards require Light and/or level 4 monsters. The only problem I've run into with this deck is anything that have more than 3 negates and a monster that is unaffected by card effects and that has a high atk as the highest potential atk this deck can achieve is 4400 with Arcanite magician with Aiwass but no protection, alternatively you can have Zoroa with Aiwass and/or other extra deck cards to have it negate all extra deck monsters matching the same type as the equiped card.

Aside from those problems I've been able to prevail against many decks specifically those that heavily rely on the extra deck, through the use of magistus, the graveyard, through the use of exosisters, and main decks through the use of everything, primairly from the use of removal by banish by exosisters and inturptions and monster stealing through fusions and big beatsticks by magistus. 

 

So far the popular decks I've beaten so far are Floo, Tearlaments, Edlitch, marincess, and labrynth. There are also decent altnerative side cards you can play namely dynatherium, D.D crow, and shallow grave. you can also potentially play quintet magician (Good luck with that) I've found that its most consistant to play it with Keeper of dragon magic and magicalized fusion, as it is a level 4 monster and a spell card that can be used by summoner monk.

Search for Gren Maiju and Banish as many cards as possible from your deck to grow his attack and defense to trumendous amounts. The side deck can be interswapped with some cards in the deck to make a more masterduel approach to this deck.

A semi-control subterror+dogmatika deck. Uses the dogmatika cards as destruction and the subterror cards as banishing and negation. If you want 3 TCBOO, that works, just remember you can only control one copy of each of the three-of in this deck (as always). The reason Kumongous is in the side deck instead of Gameciel is in case you want to use Subterror Succession to search for it (though that requires a higher level Subterror Behemoth, which I haven't put in this deck). It also works in general since it's only 200 ATK above Gameciel.

Activate Hidden City->search for Guru (Fiendess if you have Guru, and Nemesis Archer if you have both)->Set Guru->Hidden City effect->Add Fiendess, or Archer, or Final Battle/Cave Clash. Cave Clash can pull off Guru's quick effect without needing another monster. If you can't get Guru on field and Fiendess in hand, then go for the Ecclesia->Punishment line if you can. I've never used Terrors In the Hidden City, so its use in this Deck is so far unknown.

There aren't really a lot of FLIP monsters to synergize with in this deck. You could maybe argue the pot of greed FLIP monster, but there really isn't a cheap way to summon it. There are some other decent subterror behemoths, particularly the one that flips all other monsters facedown without targeting, but most other than Umastryx are kinda meh. Umastryx itself is also targeted, but adding Ultramafus can get some untargetable monsters off the field with either Archer or Umastryx. Alternatively, Subterror Succession Ultramafus for Kumongous.

Harpie's is in side Deck cause this deck can harshly lose to spells and traps- though N'tiss and some other dogmatika cards can help with this as well. One fun thing is that Final Battle can stop the negation effects of Skill Drain, Ash, Called By, and some others as well, which is why it's at 2. Plus, all 4 effects are actually pretty good, and can help you refrain from being defeated quickly.

Purrely is a archetype all about building up to big xyz by feeding your pets(monsters). most cards in the archetype are good enough to be played at 3 with some exceptions. The Happy xyz line are alright but you arent likely to go into them much until your forced to go second, then they can be good tools. The Field spell and Trap are good but searchable so 1-2 of each is better than 3.

Card Tech Explanations:

Generation force/Xyz gift:  Pot of greed(kinda). Your go to play should be making a plump then while your feeding it keep spitting out Purrely till you can make princessprite(as she is effectively a draw 1). then once both are set up and you used her effect rip the last mat off her and one mat off plump and enjoy your draws.

Shadows Light: Free purrely summon from deck without the discard cost so its good card economy, simple enough(with added bonus of being able to banish it later for an extra normal if you ever feel the need.

Dark World Monsters: They are discard fodder, they let you go deep into your monsters without slowly killing your hand(with these you can easily get 2 noirs up turn 1).

Overlay Network: This ones a more experimental choice, as plump can turn ANY spell/trap in the grave into a material so overlay network can let you reuse and spell/trap that you want, incredibly flexible use case in purrely.

deck_excerpt: Did somebody say Grass was legal?
deck_description:
This is my favourite deck in Master Duel, ABC Cyber Dragon. We're playing 60 cards becauseThat Grass Looks Greener is legal in this format and we want to take advantage of it to mill 1/3 of our deck and load up our GY with materials for ABC Dragon Buster and trigger Cyber Dragon Herz, maybe mill a target for Nachster as well. Best case scenario, we end on at least 1 ABC Dragon Buster for an interruption, 1 Cyber Dragon infinity for an omninegate, a Cyber Dragon Sieger for battle protection, and an I:P Masquerena so we can potentially make a 4-material Apollousa on our opponents turn using the Machine/Union monsters we summon from the banished zone on our opponents turn using ABC Dragon Buster's second effect.

 

There are a number of ways you can combo with this deck, some more consistent than others. Ideally, if you open Terraforming/Union Hangar, you'll use your normal summon on either A-Assault Core, B-Buster Dragon, or C-Crush Wyvern, and use Hangar to equip Union Driver, then use Driver's effect to equip another Machine/Union from the deck (one of them should be Buster Drake). Unauthorized Reactivation serves the same purpose. From here you can either make Masquerena or Union Carrier, if you make Carrier you can either equip Photon Orbital in order to search Galaxy Soldier and make Cyber Dragon Infinity, or equip the last Piece you need to make Dragon Buster.

 

If you don't open Hangar or 1 piece+Unauthorized Reactivation, your second best option for a normal summon is Cyber Dragon Core. This lets you search for either Cyber Emergency or Cyber Repair Plant on summon. The former searches a Cyber Dragon monster from the deck, the latter searches any Light Machine if Cyber Dragon is in your GY. Gizmek Yata allows you to summon Buster Drake and Core in the same turn, but it locks you into Machines for the turn, as does Cyber Dragon Nachsters revival effect. The best way to use Nachster is to revive it with Cyber Dragon Nova after making Masquerena or Phoenix, then triggering its revival effect once you don't care about being locked into machines for the rest of the turn.

We're playing Veiler instead of Imperm because it's a Light monster that synergizes with galaxy soldier Galaxy Soldier. Jizikiru is our Kaiju of choice because we can easily contact-fuse it away with Chimeratech Fortress Dragon, and also because it's a Light. We really want to minimize the number of non-Light monsters in our deck because of Galaxy Soldier. The rest is pretty standard stuff: Foolish to put a Machine/Union/Herz in the GY, One For One does the same thing plus puts a material on board. Some Pot spells for draw power, the 3 Ash, and, of course, we're Maxxed out on the dreaded insect.

Enjoy!

deck_name: Sky Striker Teir 0 Now!!!! - Yu-Gi-Oh! Master Duel
deck_excerpt: Sky Striker Teir 0 Now!!!! - Yu-Gi-Oh! Master Duel
deck_description: Enjoy the deck
gunkan suship

This deck solves the problems with scrap orcust, that being having unwanted cards in hand and not having enough bodies on field to combo off to the deck's full potential. The runick cards solve this by summoning hugin for an extra body on field, and using it's effect to discard any unwanted cards while grabbing a runick fountain to either use for runick stuff or to destroy off scrap wyvern to combo with. Loses to handtraps and graveyard manipulation so it's not *super* viable this format, but I still think this is a very strong deck with the ability to create some crazy boards.

 

Ideal first turn combo:

Summon scrap recycler and use it's effect to send world wand to graveyard

Summon hugin and use it's effect to discard any garnets in hand + grab runick fountain

Link into scrap wyvern and set one of any spare spell/traps in hand (or just use the runick fountain you grabbed)

Use wyvern's effect to summon back recycler and destroy it again, triggering wyvern's other effect to summon scrap golem from deck and destroying the set card

Use golem's effect to summon back recycler, then use recycler's effect again to send cyber-stein to the graveyard

Link into lib, using it's effect to set world legacy succession from the deck

Use succession to summon cyber-stein to lib's link arrow

link wyvern and lib into cross-sheep, making sure not to trigger the lib (lol)

use cyber-stein to go into exterio in a zone cross-sheep is pointing to, using it's effect to summon back recycler

use recycler effect to send orcust knightmare, using it's effect to send cymbal skeleton, then summoning knightmare using world wand's effect

link into galatea, using it's effect to shuffle back world wand and set orcust crescendo

overlay dingirsu on top of galatea and link into I:P masquerena using dingirsu and cyber-stein

use cymbal skeleton to summon back galatea so you can use crescendo next turn

 

This leaves you with infinite spell/trap negates, an omni negate in case of dark ruler no more/droplet, and an apollousa/avramax/unicorn protected from card effects

If you get handtrapped at any point in this your turn is usually over, in which you hope and pray that you can draw decent stuff with the runick engine.

Anyway, hope you enjoy the deck!

deck_name: Train Beatdown (with Kaijus !) on a Budget
deck_excerpt: OTK your opponnent with this affordable (40-60$) beatdown deck composed of Trains with lots of removal and Rank 10 support
deck_description:
For anyone familiar with the LV10/RK10 Train strategy, nothing out of the ordinary here, pretty easy to figure out !

Kaijus are there both for easy removal and for Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju being a LV10 Machine monster (can be really useful and consistent with the related spell card Interrupted Kaiju Slumber)

Exodius the Ultimate Forbidden Lord provides both an easy to summon LV10 monster and GY recycling capabilities, allowing for more material tutoring from the deck in case the duel lasts for a while, notably with the help of Revolving Switchyard (don't forget to send cards such as Ruffian Railcar, Super Express Bullet Train or Machina Citadel to the GY for best results)

A useful trick to keep in mind in case there is more than one problematic card that needs to be destroyed is using Skypalace Gangaridai with Heavy Freight Train Derricrane as one of its XYZ materials in order to pop any two cards on the field (since it's two different effects being activated, there's chances at least one destruction effect will still go through)

Even though it's pretty cheap, this deck still has enough going for it to be able to compete in some locals (especially with the Side Deck), it's also nice to use in Master Duel at the very least until Gold Rank, definitely worth trying either way !

deck_excerpt: Phantom Knight, Adventure, Destiny HERO, Master Duel
deck_description:
Playing the deck going first you want to find a way to put 2 level 3's in play for Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss . Use that to send Water Enchantress of the Temple  and that unlocks the entire Adventure line letting you set up Wandering Gryphon Rider  before comitting to The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche  the heart and soul of the deck. From there you want to navigate setting up Phantom Knight names in the GY for the following turn and try to make Artifact Dagda and trigger it's effect before using it and any extra material you have on board for Predaplant Verte Anaconda to get out Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer that you can use to pop your set Artifact Scythe or even use Rusty Bardiche's 2nd effect by reviving Break Sword to its Link point.

When playing 2nd; Forbidden Droplet and the adventure engine will take you pretty far. You want to weave through Cherubini still but ensure you can resolve your Rusty Bardiche. If your opponent has an established board using The Phantom Knights of Break Sword can clear a problem monster then if you pop itself you can revive the materials as level 4's to make Raider's Knight then rank up into Arc Rebellion Xyz Dragon which can probably OTK by itself.

You die to Dimension Shifter Barrier Statue of the Stormwinds Archnemeses Protos There Can Be Only One and Artifact Scythe as well as it is very dangerous to play through Maxx "C" since you cannot deck someone out even if you open a perfect hand.

The best opening hand for the deck is Rite of Aramesir Water Enchantress of the Temple The Phantom Knights of Torn Scales Fusion Destiny and any other Phantom Knight, Danger or handtrap.

Other alternatives for more extenders/consistancy boosts are Speedroid Taketomborg Speedroid Terrortop Psychic Wheeleder Psychic Tracker Emergency Teleport Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit These can let you get into Cherubini's much eaiser wihout commiting to any of your Phantom Knight extenders.

deck_excerpt: If you can't decide on what you want to play, just play everything!
deck_description:
Punk Adventure Ishizu Naturia Therion Vernuslyph

The Earth attribute archetypes lived seperated until the day the DUCK was released. Since then they have formed a conglomerate that can even beat the strongest of Tear 0 decks (provided your opponent doesn't draw Nibiru, Shifter or Droll & Lock).

 

The deck is really fun to play. While the individual engines are striaghtforward, combining the combo lines and trying to figure out how to optimally play a hand feels very rewarding and the deck plays surpisingly different to all currently viable decks.

The Punk engine brings the explosive combo plays and enable a lot of the other engines.
The Adventure engine grants protection and card advantage and enables different combo routes.
The Ishizu cards are oviously strong against graveyard reliant decks, but also recycle resources and are searchable (kind of).
The Naturia cards are incredibly synergistic and enable some crazy endboards.
The Therion engine grants some needed protection after the Vernusylph restriction and also generate a lot of advantage.
The Vernusylph cards tie this whole mess together. Hail the DUCK!

You can put up some really strong boards that are sometimes unbeatable and it doesn't brick as often as you would assume looking at the list. Though it's sometimes impossible to activate some engines depending on the hand.
The Punk trap, the searchable Klebek and Mole Cricket allow to play through Dark Ruler and Droplet suprisingly easily. Different setups also make this deck really hard to deal with and sometimes allow for instant wins.
Going second also isn't as bad, since you can push through quite a bit of interaction, especially if you draw Vernusylphs in combination with other engines. Resolving the same Scrap Dragon multiple times via the Vernusylphs is not only strong, but also really funny.

The biggest downside of the deck is that it's almost impossible to side deck. Since 57/60 cards are engine cards and the only non-engine card, Fenrir, might as well be one, there is nothing to be side out. Also considering that it's a 60-card deck means that you have to side in almost all of it, if not in it's entirety, going second. Therefore I build the side in a way were you can either side out the entire adventure engine or the Therion, Ishizu and 1-of Adventure and Deer Note for the entire side before the Lifetrancer.
Lifetrancer is your win-con for time, Barrierstatue is an optional win-con going first and Zombie World is GG against Floo.

Another downside is, that there is no room for tech slots. You might be able to shave some cards to get maybe 2 to 5 slots open, but thats probably it, unless you cut an engine like Therion or Ishizu entirely. You cloud consider to cut the Adventure engine, but the value and protection it grants is most likely too important.
The same problem also arises if you consider the ever shifting meta game. Depending on where the meta goes, it could happen that this deck won't be able win a singular match.

But most importantly is that the acronym is P.A.I.N. T.V.! We are truly blessed by the DUCK for such an acronym!
