deck_excerpt: (...) A breathtakingly beautiful world of ice and water appeared before their eyes
deck_description:
Icejades, the "Krawlers" of the Abyss storyline finally got their own "Krawler Suma" that helps the deck in insane ways, but first lets get acquainted to the playstyle of these crystaline rulers of the Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle .

Icejades one of the most convoluted floodgate that requires 3 cards to get its full potential, requiring Your majesty Icejade Kosmochlor which makes monsters your opponent control only be able to activate their effects in the turn they are summoned if their domain is activated in your field zone Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle , this majestic place fetches dead or banished Icejades and adds them back to your hand, and if you special summon a water monster it can lower the attack equal to the targeted monster's attack. And if both are on the field Icejade Curse comes in and stops the effects of your opponent's monsters from activating the turn they were summoned + giving you some burn damage in case your monsters die. Its kinda insane but since its too hard to pull off consistently it comes in a more grind game'ish scenario.

Two of your most important monsters are Icejade Aegirine and Icejade Aegirine Rahn , the prior fetches an icejade S/T including their Non-opt Rota Icejade Cradle , Altergeist Manifestation which requires your opponent to either control or have in their GY a monster to SS or send to the GY an icejade from deck with a banish effect if one of your monsters die, or Icejade Erosion which we will get to later... she also has an effect to protect herself and summon a water from hand of GY in case she is targeted. As for her grown up form, Rahn allows you to discard any Icejade card or water monster to summon herself and a token in a Swordsoul Like manner (Swordsoul Strategist Longyuan), and locking you into waters, with these 2 you can summon their boss monster Icejade Aegirine Gymir which is just insane, field protection from most forms of removal besides Send/Tribute/Bounce which also banishes the card its activation responded to + copies of it in case there are any in the GY or field and being able to revive herself if a card is banished, or make Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying , other plays involve Marincess Coral Anemone to summon back the Rahn.

As for the other Jades, you are using them because of Cradles restriction and for their GY effect in which they can banish themselves if an Icejade is destroyed to summon it back on the field, which can also be triggered by their negate trap Icejade Erosion . Tremora you run at 3 because its a free special summon of any water monster including their only other tuner Icejade Creation Aegirocassis which after tuning you can equip it to your synchro. 

The ed contains some basic water links, I:P package and some R4nk water monsters like Bahamut Shark for Toadally Awesome , Abyss Dweller and Number 4: Stealth Kragen 

The support is pretty nice for a deck that couldnt even put their synchro on board because of their only tuner being terrible, hopefully konami will give us one more card to help the deck, but for now its serviceable!

deck_excerpt: Flower Cardian, Diamond, Combo, Master Duel
deck_description:
I don't want to play Yugioh today... No problem it's Flower Cardian time! No no no wait! It's not as difficult and boring as you think. My goal today is to explain Flower Cardian as simple as possible and tell you why it's so strong, let's start:

The VERY important Starters

In this Deck you will find 13 Cards which get things started, every other card is essencially a Brick at first. Sounds terrible but the odds of drawing at least one starter are on your side 90% of the time from my experience. 

For the Spells the 1x Flower Gathering and the 3x Super Koi Koi are the starters. 3x Flower Stacking can prepare a Starter for the following turn if you can survive one turn with an empty board. 

The Monster Starters are the 3x Level 1 Pine (The grey colored one), 3x Cherry Blossom (The red and pink colored one) and 3x Cherry Blossom with Curtain (the purple colored one). 

You have to draw one of these 13 Starters or you can't play the game at all. Flower Stacking kinda brings it to 16 Cards if you manage to survive one turn.

I don't like playing more then one Flower Gathering since Ash Blossom negates it and it's the only card which doesn't gain advantage of any kind when it's milled to the GY.

 

The general Idea behind the Cardians

Whenever you summon a Flower Cardian monster you will almost always Draw 1 Card and show it, if it's another Flower Cardian Monster you keep it in your Hand, if it's a Spell you discard it to the Graveyard. 

Almost all Flower Cardian cards have no Once per turn so it's easy to go through your whole 40 card Deck as early as turn one to create big Synchro Boss Monsters.

You want to use one of the three different tuners which all share the ability to change the level of all Monsters you control to 2 for a Synchro summon to create these Synchro Bosses. That means you have to summon many Cardian Monsters to get out many Synchro Monsters in one turn. 

5 Cardians = LV10 Synchro Monster

4 Cardians = LV8 Synchro Monster

3 Cardians = LV6 Synchro Monster

 

The three different Cardian types

Every Cardian can be placed into one of three categories: 

The free special summons

These Cardians can special themselves onto the field when a Cardian with a lower level then themselves already exists on the field. They always have 100 ATK and DEF.

The one tributes

These type of Cardians can special themselves by tributing any other Cardian Monster on the field and always draw one card when they are summoned. They always have 1000 ATK and DEF. 

The specific tribute ones

The last type of Cardians can only be special summoned by tributing a Cardian with the same level which is already on the field. They always draw one card on summon and can special the drawn card if it's a monster. They always have 2000 ATK and DEF. 

 

The Goal for Turn one

The best thing you can aim for initially is to special summon the 3 Synchro Bosses onto the field. The LV10 Lightflare, LV8 Lightshower and the LV6 Boardefly. 

With that you get a Spell & Trap negation with 5K attack which gives the ability to negate Monster effects during Battle for all Cardians and replaces itself with any other Cardian Synchro Monster if it leaves the field by the opponent.

A 3K tower that gives targeting and destruction protection to all Cardians and burns the opponent for 1500 during his Draw Phase. 

And a 2K boy who gives piercing to all Cardian Monsters and prevents Monster effects and Special summons from the Graveyard.

In short a very formidable Board that can easily Deal with Meta threats and easily OTK the opponent. 

 

Additional Spice 

If your Synchro Board gets broken through mainly non targeting Removal you can use the Spell Super All In to revive any 4 Cardian Monsters from the GY and special a 5th by drawing it. The big downside if you fail to draw a Cardian can be prevented with Lightshowers destruction protection (I had to read this 3 times to understand how it works).

The Maindeck Monsters can change the order of the top 3 cards of the opponents Deck or place them on the bottom. Extremely useful in Master Duel to find out what you are up against. You have access to non targeting Monster and Backrow destruction too. Even a 1000 ATK gain Handtrap is part of the Maindeck lineup and the Moonflowerviewing Synchro can enable a 2k direct attack with her effect. 

 

Tips from me for beginners with this Deck

The L6 Synchro Moonflowerviewing can enable a Draw 1 which is 100% safe meaning you don't have to discard the card even if it's a Spell. Very useful if the cards don't fall into your favor to keep advantage going. 

The green colored LV11 Willow Cardian in the Maindeck is very important. His effect allows to recycle 1 Cardian from grave back into the Deck to Draw 1 card. This card draw is 100% safe again so no discarding even if it's a Spell. The level 8 Zebra Grass can also enable safe Draws but is less useful in that regard. Try to loop Willows effect as often as possible by recycling Willow with Willow.

Don't Panic if you don't find tuners fast enough sometimes. A Board of 5 different 2K beaters is often formidable enough to clear the game too especially with all the non targeting Removal which is accessible for you. 

Special summon the LV10 Synchro first. He's useful for it's negation and ability to be any other Flower Cardian Synchro should he leave the field. Be sure to summon him in the Extra Monster Zone to have space for the others. 

And lastly special your Cardians with 100 ATK in defense. If the opponent interrupts you, you will be glad to have them in defense. 

 

Final Words

This Deck doesn't play the Yugioh you know and it somehow works very well. It's easy to reach Diamond in Master Duel with this Strategy but beware your biggest enemy Nibiru. The usual offenders like Kaijus, non targeting Banish and Barrier Statue stun also work well against this Strategy so if you can choose go first. 

You will win many games from the opponent scooping since this Archetype is known for it's long turns. If you want quick wins it's kinda possible with this Deck simply because 50% of the time the opponent will surrender to not watch you go full Combo. 

If you choose to pick this Deck up you will notice how much fun playing Cardians can be (The opponent may have less fun). I like these based on Hanafuda fellas a lot. 

Overall Rating: ★★★★★☆

deck_excerpt: subterror, teamdrawphase, yugioh,meta deck, gurucontrol, kashtira, dogmatika, tearlaments, sprights, control, anti-meta,
deck_description:
The idea behind this Guru Control build is to supress monster effects and opponent outs as much as possible.

Through the use of, tried and proven, Guru Control, you will contract Battle Phases with Hidden City and disrupt with Guru and Fiendess. Kasthira Fenrir is insurance for when you brick, hardly ever happens, or get interrupted and you need a safety net. Fenrir acts as a boss monster while slowing down your opponents decision making.

The dogmatika core is the tank, the shield of the deck. It's anti-meta prowess adds allure to beatdown and assists with multiple disruptins through Fluer and Punishment. A true control build with new flair- faster and more oppresive thats for sure!

The win condition is to control and suppress reaction and board builder up, followed by beatdowns from Fluer, Fenrir, Guru and/or Umastryx. In the side, we have the Bystial package that is phenomenal right now because we are in a dark format, and light trails ever so closely- and with GY being so relied upon, Bystial ensure disruption to punish opponents and cause potential misplays, or backtracks.

Overall, a fun yet meta contending build.

deck_excerpt: All Machiner Units Report to Commander Covington immediately- it's time Redeploy and establish a Defense Perimeter!
deck_description:
Historically, Machina have been a pretty consistent supplementary component to the EARTH Machine strategies of Trinity. Often times they are combined with Ancient Gear, Gadgets, Orcust, and even Cyber Dragons; however, today I present to you a strategy meant to cater to putting on full display the capabilities of the Machina force without the assistance of others (barring... some Infinitrack cards because we just need to fill the deck space okay...?) Got it? Good, let me brief you on the deck here:

Pros:

 

  • Resistance: Formerly used to have a problem against banishing, up until we got Ruinforce to remedy that problem entirely. Now, even if your Machinas are removed from play, you can rely on Ruinforce to put them back in circulation AND trigger any on-summon effects in the process. It's quite potent and makes them a deck that works well regarding both the GY and banished pile. And should your Ruinforce ever be banished, you can just resolve the GY effect of Overdrive to shuffle it back in.

 

  • Arsenal: The Infinitracks allow the Machinas to manipulate their levels to access a plethora of toolboxed options in the Extra Deck. Though those options aren't always needed as the Machina cards themselves function very well together to establish a fortification between hand, field, and GY that can be rather annoying to deal with if managed properly.

 

  • Easy to Pick Up: Once you get used to the lines and how the cards talk to one another, you'll find that the deck is pretty straightforward to pilot, especially since almost everything in here is an Effect Monster anyway. You'll mostly be rewarded for your usage tactical trades with Fortress or navigating complex gamestates with Air Raider, Irradiator, Resavenger, and the Machina Spell/Trap combo. It sounds like a lot on paper, but it's not too bad... maybe. Look, just find Limiter Removal and use it with Ruinforce to instantly win the duel.

 

Cons:

 

  • Infinitracks: The Infinitrack Monsters, while great for adding diversity and options to the deck, unfortunately eat up a LOT of summons to get going. It's best to use them as a backup or to establish a River Stormer. If you've got Drill or Harvester, consider just using them to cheat out Xyzs rather than for standard Infinitrack lines. This isn't an Infinitrack-focused deck after all.

 

  • Little Protection: The only real searchable protection we have in this deck is through Defense Perimeter's continous benefits and that is more like a lightning rod than a diffuser. You'll want to think with less of a mindset of protecting the castle and more about how to breach the opponent's. Trade well and you'll be rewarded for it. Don't and... it'll be pretty challenging to deal with some backrows and board breaking monsters.

 

  • Inconsistent Interaction: All of this deck's ways of dealing with the opponent primarily deal with board-breaking already established boards or hard drawing specific forms of removal. We are playing Harmonizer Gradielle and Tornado Dragon but calling those cards reliable disruption across the board is a little generous.

 

Now that the briefing's over, let's get you sortied.

 



OPENERS

Machina's playstyle is pretty different from its TCG Advance counterpart since we don't have access to Citadel and the crazy setups that card can get up to. Instead, we'll just have to settle for board breaking and mid-range with a pretty decent top end if we happen to go wide with our various Emergency Teleport-like effects. Let's start with the basics.

 

  • Machina Redeployment: This card's absurdly potent and enables so many various lines of play that it's honestly baffling that this card is allowed at three copies. Now, the two modes this card offers you are very different in what lines of play you get access to. Starting with the first mode of discarding any card, you'll want to grab Machina Gearframe and any other Machina Monster of your choosing that is not Unclaspare. I recommend going for a level 4 like Possesstorage so you have a follow-up play or Resavenger so you can opt to just stop on two monsters, or potentially three if you opened one that can Special Summon itself. Use Gearframe to grab Unclaspare then use its effect to summon itself from the hand. Bin either Fortress or Ruinforce and decide if you'll go into Gear Gigant X or not. If you do, you'll want to use Gear to pick up Ancient Gear Box and usually Anchor Drill to have a guaranteed Rank 4 or 8 follow-up play with no restrictions. The other targets for Gigant X are also valid, but this option's definitely the safest one to go with in most scenarios. Regarding the second mode will depend a lot on the Machina card that is discarded, but for simplicity's sake, let's just assume it's a card that is a Monster not named Ruinforce. You'll want to pick up Possesstorage and Machina Overdrive. You'll just toss down Possesstorage and loop the monster back then set Overdrive and you're good to go in the simplest of cases. Use Overdrive to pivot into either Fortress, Air Raider, or Metalcruncher as necessary. If you're looking for something more aggresive, feel free to go for an early Fortress play with Redeployment and pick up Defense Perimeter. This will make it so that Fortress is always the attack target for your little guys and will draw all monster targeting effects, helping to resolve its handloop effect at resolution. That a lot to take in? Well it shouldn't be, it's the first card we've talked about thus far!

 

  • Machina Overdive: Sometimes you don't open too well or just need a way to catch up quickly because you've bricked on a high level Machina. You'll use Overdrive to tag into Metalcruncher then pick up Gearframe, Ancient Gear Box, or Flying Pegasus. If you have a Machina in hand you'll also want to consider Air Raider and Irradiator as they enable some pretty fantastic pivots when playing from behind to quickly get back into the game. Pegasus can be used with Metalcruncher to Earthslice the board apart or explore a number of other Xyz options to deal with the opponent's armada. Box's virtually the same way, picking up Anchor Drill, but if you're really far behind consider going for Gigant X and finding Gearframe to get your Machinas continuing to cycle.

 

  • Dragonlark Pairen: If you happen to find yourself in a scenario where you have Harvester but no way to benefit from it because the levels are 6 when combined, then you can go into Pairen. With the first Harvester search, ideally you'll pick up Brutal Dozer, but if you need a discard outlet for whatever reason, you'll go with Trencher instead. Then, during the opponent's Standby Phase, you'll use the detach effect to detach Harvester and pick up another search which will usually be Anchor Drill. If the other material attached to Pairen is worth summoning back as well, then by all means feel free to go for that one instead. Pairen will inherently protect itself and draw aggression while also redirecting things back to your resurrected monster, giving you some time to be in the driver's seat and fill up your hand a bit despite not actually putting up a form of disruption. Neat huh?

 

The openings won't always need to be the same, but they are extremely consistent which feels refreshing when it comes to limited formats where most of the cards are one-ofs so you'll often find no two openers looking the same. Once you're more comfortable with identifying your Air Raiders from your Irradiators and such you'll pick up your own openers that best suit your hand and opponent to better accomodate the Machina strategy.

MIDGAME

Most midgames with the deck will just feature you going quite wide or having game planned ahead by a couple moves and setting up Ruinforce in GY to be there when it's time to throw down. As such, the plays featured in this section will mostly just highlight some of the all-stars that could be easily missed at a glance.

 

  • Double Headed Anger Knuckle: You'll only really go for this with Super Express Bullet Train unless you've got a cheeky Knightmare Unicorn play in mind. You'll want to keep looping the two together to get free cards back from your GY thanks to Bullet Train's EP effect. Combine this with Ancient Gear Box in the GY and you'll be turning that add back from the GY into a search from the deck!

 

  • Dhampir Vampire Sheridan: This card breaks boards and outs things like Dark End Dragon... then can also just steal them like Goyo Guardian- huh. In any case, this card's great to go into with a mid-game Harvester for putting a dent in your opponent's defenses if you can't amass the levels to go into something like a Dingirsu who will give you a similar benefit but will provide your field with passive protection instead or Sky Dragon Overlord to protect your board and GY from being banished and bounced around.

 

  • Machina Resavenger: Combined with your offensive, this card can really just be a nuisance and turn your Machinas into much, much stronger threats than what your opponent is comfortable with running into or being run over by. Using it to overpower something Honest-style will just add it back to hand too, re-establishing its presence and putting you further in control. If you ever happen to lose it too, you can always fetch it back with Irradiator, Possesstorage, and Defense Perimeter.

 


This deck doesn't really fancy a grind game, so the next section is more so dedicated to some clean finisher options to look out for.

LATEGAME & CLOSERS

 

  • Machina Ruinforce: This card's absolutely bloated with all sorts of benefits and perks and it's all the better when actually played with Machinas because it has such a massive target on its back that demands it be answered. You'll want to plan ahead with your levels banished to summon it usually with a Possesstorage, Fortress, or Metalcruncher so that way when Ruinforce gets ruined, you can have a really strong recovery to keep up the pressure and come out on top regarding the trade. Once you enter the battle phase, do not be afraid of anything at all. Paying half your LP will hardly matter in most games, especially since it halves your opponent's LP by the same effect. With this monster being a 1 Summon 4.6k beatstick, that means once the BP is entered, you can freely clear anything you'd like to (and even use fast effects like Tornado Dragon, Overdrive, and other things) and not have to worry about the opponent responding because if they do, they probably lose immediately.

 

  • Limiter Removal: Does this card really need any introduction?

 

  • Liebe: This one's a little tricky to setup since we're not a Rank 10 Railway build but it's definitely an option thanks to the Infinitracks and Pegasus. This will primarily be setup from an Anger Knuckle play or Urgent Schedule on your opponent's turn, then on your turn you'll go into Gangaridai and blow something up (ideally backrow) for 1k damage, then go into Liebe and swing for game. Just remember that Liebe only gets the bonus attacks against monsters, not just in general.

 


The lines presented by the Machina archetype are really consistent, resilient, and flexible, sporting a variety of options and synergies that only continue to improve as the cardpool expands. Thanks to these qualities and Konami's unification of Machines in general, you can try some of the following things to switch up your approach on Machina here:

Allure of Darkess, Mekk-Knight, Orcust, Cyber Dragon & Clockwork Night, Revolving Switchyard, Fossil Fusion, Gadgets, Crystrons, Ancient Gear, and EARTH Tuners for Naturia Barkion.

And that's the end of this transmission, Cadet. Hope all of that information wasn't too much for you. Believe me when I say it's a lot easier than it reads- epsecially when it comes to scenarios after resolving Redeployment the first time in a game. I'll continue to iterate on strategies and post guides here, you should probably leave this Armored Unit now. We'll want you in Megaform if you ever want to promote from a Soldier to an Air Raider- all in the name of being a Peacekeeper of course!

2.

5.

"Infernoble Knight - Renaud" effect on summon, Return to hand "Infernoble Arms - Durendal".

 

6.

Equip and Active the effect of  "Infernoble Arms - Durendal", Search "Infernoble Knight - Renaud"

Then Special summon "Infernoble Knight - Renaud".

 

Link summon "Union Carrier" using "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights" and "Infernoble Knight - Renaud".

"Union Carrier" effect, Equip "Box of Friends".

 

7.

Link summon "Relinquished Anima" using the other "Infernoble Knight - Renaud".

"Relinquished Anima" effect, Equip "Union Carrier",

"Box of Friends" send to graveyard, Special summon "Metalfoes Steelen" and "Igknight Squire".

 

8.

Link summon "Heavymetalfoes Electrumite" using "Metalfoes Steelen" and "Igknight Squire".

"Heavymetalfoes Electrumite" effect on summon, Send "Dark Doriado" form Deck to EX Deck.

"Heavymetalfoes Electrumite" effect, Destroy "Union Carrier" in Spell & Trap Zone, Return either "Metalfoes Steelen" or "Igknight Squire" Form Ex Deck.

 

9. 

Set P Scale using "Yoko-Zuna Sumo Spirit" and the Returned Monster ("Metalfoes Steelen" or "Igknight Squire").

Pendulum Summon "Dark Doriado" and the P Monster left in the Ex Deck ("Metalfoes Steelen" or "Igknight Squire").

"Yoko-Zuna Sumo Spirit"  Chain 1,  "Dark Doriado"  Chain 2.

 

"Dark Doriado" place "Rescue Ferret", "Deep Sea Diva", "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring", and any "Battlewasp" to Top of the Deck in order.

"Heavymetalfoes Electrumite" Draw 1 card.

 

10.

Link summon "Saryuja Skull Dread" using 4 Monsters on the Field. 

"Saryuja Skull Dread" on Summon Draw 4 Cards, then Place the Cards that need to send to Graveyard (e.g. "Mezuki" )back to Deck in any order. 

"Saryuja Skull Dread"  effect, Special summon "Rescue Ferret" in hand. 

"Rescue Ferret" effect, Special summon "Dotscaper", "Virtual World Hime - Nyannyan", and any Level 2 Tuner Monster form Deck.

 

11.

Synchro summon "Muddy Mudragon"

"Dotscaper" effect, Special summon itself back from Graveyard.

"Muddy Mudragon" effect, Fusion summon "Cyberse Clock Dragon" using itself and "Saryuja Skull Dread".

**DO NOT ACTIVATE "Cyberse Clock Dragon" effect now.

 

12.

Link summon "Clock Lizard" using "Cyberse Clock Dragon" and "Dotscaper"

"Clock Lizard" effect, Fusion summon "Cyberse Clock Dragon"

**The Fusion Material LINK RATE needs to be the SAME AMOUNT AS the cards LEFT IN THE DECK**

 

13.

"Cyberse Clock Dragon" effect on summon, Send all cards in Deck to Graveyard.

"Tour Bus From the Underworld" effect when sent to Graveyard, Return "Holactie the Creator of Light" back to Deck.

Activate Effect of "Chaos Space" in Graveyard, Return any Light or Dark Ex Deck Monster, Draw 1 card.

(In this case, it will definitely be "Holactie the Creator of Light")

 

14. 

"Fairy Tail - Snow" effect, Special summon itself by Banish 7 cards Include "Virtual World Hime - Nyannyan" and "Zombie World"

"Virtual World Hime - Nyannyan" effect when Banish, Return "Zombie World" back to Deck.

"Necroworld Banshee" effect, Activate "Zombie World" from Deck.

 

15.

Activate 3 "Mezuki" effects in Graveyard,

Special summon "Slifer the Sky Dragon" from Graveyard.

Special summon "Obelisk the Tormentor" from Graveyard.

Special summon one of Any Monster in from Graveyard.

** one of "Slifer the Sky Dragon" or "Obelisk the Tormentor" Need to be right UNDER the Extra Monster Zone.

 

16.

Link summon "Knightmare Unicorn" using Monster APART from "Slifer the Sky Dragon" AND "Obelisk the Tormentor" 

(Don't need to Activate the effect of "Knightmare Unicorn")

 

"Fairy Tail - Snow" effect, Special summon itself by Banish 7 cards. (NO "Monster Reborn" and "Dark Spell Regeneration")

 

17.

Link summon "Knightmare Gryphon" using "Fairy Tail - Snow" and "Knightmare Unicorn" 

"Knightmare Gryphon" effect, Discard 1 card, Set "Monster Reborn" from Graveyard.

 

18.

Activate effect of "Dark Spell Regeneration" in Garveyard, Send the Set "Monster Reborn" from Feild to Graveyard, 

Special summon "The Winged Dragon of Ra" from Graveyard.

 

19.

Special summon "Holactie the Creator of Light " by Tributing "Slifer the Sky Dragon", "Obelisk the Tormentor", and "The Winged Dragon of Ra". 

 

20.

Victory by the effect of Holactie.

 

 

 

p.s. "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring" can be change any Fire Monster

deck_excerpt: Beat as hard as you can!
deck_description: This is my deck from EDOpro, I think it's a really strong and fun EARTH-machine deck.
A fun combination of cards that combines the Aroma, Sunavalon, and Adventure cards to permit a deck that just does not quit hanging around.

BRANDED DESPIA BUDGET 30€

As a Branded player I tried to create a Branded Despia decklist cheaper that i could!

30€ to be... yeah pretty competitive!

 

The list is created using mainly the structure deck cards of "Albaz Strike", adding some cheap cards you need as the despia packet and the edge imp engine

I cut Alubers and the Branded Openings to save as much budget I could, you can still use Kitt and Keeper to search Branded Fusion 

I also obv cut the Super Polys and their targets

 

about the SIDE: that's not a real side obviously! I just wanted to give you some options for your decklist!

- you can play the Disciple or Scythe lock using Branded Expulsion

- Dark Ruler No More is a perfect going second card if you don't have Super Poly, you can put them even in the main deck if you think you need them! (You find them in the structure)

- Gold Sarcophagus could be a good choiche to have another way to add Branded Fusion (banish Mercourier, add Kitt, effect Kitt to add Branded Fusion)

- Branded Sword could be switched with Branded Retribution as a Albion foolish burial target

- Effect Veiler it's ok as light target for Albion fusion summon instead of Ecclesia, anyway I still prefer her, but you know... it's a budget profile and Veiler is in the structure!

 

Wait do you still have money to spend? The first things you must buy are definitely 3x Aluber and 3x Branded Opening to replace Kitt and Keeper, oh well you should even buy some sleeves ahah, you don't want to mess up your cards!

deck_excerpt: A secret organization formed to travel across time and dimensions to defeat all evil!
deck_description:
S-force or Security Force are one of the 7'ish Column based decks and for most people watered down Mekk-Knights, but lets look at the positives that this Justice League has! 

S-forces can play under two incredible floodgates There Can Be Only One and Dimension Shifter Likes, this build doesnt run Tcboo since their new support conflicts with it, S-Force Nightchaser their newest Link-1 helps their swarming by bouncing any of your S-forces which includes itself to summon one banished S-Force monster, now you gotta be asking yourself "Frog do they have a way to banish their own cards?" and the answer would be kinda S-Force Rappa Chiyomaru is the main way you will be banishing since she can banish from hand to summon any S-Force from deck, S-Force Orrafist and S-Force Lapcewell can also banish from your hand but you wont be seeing them in the field too often, some of their cards do help to balance out the banishing, S-Force Retroactive and S-Force Chase can banish themselves from the Gy instead of you banishing an S-force from hand and S-Force Pla-Tina helps them revive the banished S-forces.

And thats kinda why you run Bystials in the deck, 3x Bystial Magnamhut , 1x Bystial Druiswurm and 1x Bystial Baldrake , because all S-forces are Light or Dark monsters that like to be banished! Which also lets the deck run Dimension Shifter and Topologic Zeroboros .

Now at the start of this I mentioned how they are a part of the Column mechanic gang, their effects apply in all columns that you control S-force monsters, Pla-tina makes them lose 600Atk, Rappa makes so they can only target monsters in their own column, Orrafist can QEff banish from hand to pop a monster that activated its effect, Gravitino is works like Fissure, Razor stops them from going into Link-3s or higher, Lapcewell nukes those columns, Dog Tag stops your opponent from activating effects. Their effects are all over the place, the ones you care most about would be Gravitino and their boss monster S-Force Justify which can drag monsters to its column to negate their effect as long as he points to them and can banish every monster it points to when it battles.

The deck is a little better now with Nightchase, but it still needs some extra support to get a more competitive edge, which hopefully will be granted to us in the future, but until then watch out your columns...? Maybe one day aliens will become meta and Alien Infiltrator will be a broken meta destroying card, 800 direct attack? that like, powercreeps Penguin Torpedo lol?
